05165nam a22006375i 9780773555402DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735554027 a10.1515/97807735554022doi  a(DE-B1597)654833  a(OCoLC)1048895919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPG3476.G7 7aLIT0042402bisacsh04a891.73/4222300aVasily Grossman :bA Writer's Freedom /ced. by Anna Bonola, Giovanni Maddalena. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b4 b&w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction -- tFree at Last: Vasily Grossman and the Battle for Stalingrad -- tGrossman and the Tradition of Classical Russian Literature -- tIdeological Words and Words from Life in Life and Fate by Vasily Grossman -- tEverything Flows but Ivan Grigorevich Stands Still: Grossman, Heraclitus, and the Prodigal Son -- tA Few Sad Short Stories: A Closer Look at Grossman's Later Works -- t“What Is Human in Man”: The Levels of Freedom in Vasily Grossman -- tThe Russian Idea, Lenin, and the Origins of the Totalitarian State in Vasily Grossman's Forever Flowing -- tVasily Grossman, Human Rights, and Political Institutions -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVasily Grossman (1905–1964) was a successful Soviet author and journalist, but he is more often recognized in the West as Russian literature's leading dissident. How do we account for this paradox? In the first collection of essays to explore the Russian author's life and works in English, leading experts present recent multidisciplinary research on Grossman's experiences, his place in the history of Russian literature, key themes in his writing, and the wider implications of his life and work in the realms of philosophy and politics. Born into a Jewish family in Berdychiv, Grossman was initially a supporter of the ideals of the Russian Revolution and the new Soviet state. During the Second World War, he worked as a correspondent for the Red Army newspaper and was the first journalist to write about the Nazi extermination camps. As a witness to the daily violence of the Soviet regime, Grossman became more and more aware of the nature and forms of totalitarian coercion, which gradually alienated him from the Soviet regime and earned him a reputation for dissidence. A survey of the remarkable accomplishments and legacy left by this controversial and contradictory figure, Vasily Grossman reveals a writer's power to express freedom even under totalitarianism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aBonola, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonola, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCalusio, Maurizia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllis, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrard, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrard, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhini, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazarev, Lazar I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaddalena, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaddalena, Giovanni, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosboch, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re